 second about the significance of local economies, and in the third about the contributions of the public sector. Through these movements, Jane L. Collins maps a set of cultural conversations about the types of investments and activities that contribute to the health of the economy. Compelling and persuasive, The Politics of Value offers a new framework for viewing economic value, one grounded in thoughtful assessment of the social division of labor and the relationship of the state and the market to civil society.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aCommon goodxEconomic aspects. 0aCommon good. 0aEconomicsxPolitical aspects. 0aEconomicsxSociological aspects. 0aEconomics. 0aSocial movementszUnited StatesxHistoryy21st century. 0aSocial movements. 0aSocial responsibility of business. 0aValuexSocial aspects. 0aValue. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aGreat Recession.  aSlow Money.  aWisconsin Uprising.  aausterity politics.  abenefit corporations.  acorporate governance.  aeconomic value.  apublic sector.  ashareholder value.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z97831107119360 cprintz978022644600440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226446288423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226446288/original  a978-3-11-071193-6  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles